{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:04:48.391529+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have all the information needed. Here's a complete walkthrough.\n\n---\n\n## Database Migrations in `rpnr-bench/T11_R01_C01_A03`\n\n### Migration Framework\n\nMigrations are plain SQL files stored in the `migrations/` directory, numbered with a zero-padded sequence prefix. They are applied in **lexicographic (filename glob) order** by the script `scripts/apply_migrations.sh`, which iterates over `migrations/*.sql` and pipes each file into `psql` running inside the `pgdev_db` Docker container.\n\n### Migrations Present in the Repository\n\nThe `migrations/` directory currently contains **three** migration files (001–003). The `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md` references three additional migrations (004–006) that were applied historically but have since been archived out of the active `migrations/` directory — they are **not present** in the current codebase.\n\nHere they are in application order:\n\n---\n\n#### 1. `001_create_users.sql` — Initial users table\n**Applied:** 2024-11-04\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n\nCreates the foundational `users` table with:\n- An auto-incrementing `BIGSERIAL` primary key (`id`).\n- A unique, non-null `email` column (TEXT).\n- An optional `display_name` (TEXT).\n- A `created_at` timestamp with timezone, defaulting to the current time.\n\n---\n\n#### 2. `002_create_sessions.sql` — Sessions table with foreign key\n**Applied:** 2024-12-10\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\nCreates the `sessions` table:\n- Primary key is a `UUID`.\n- `user_id` is a required foreign key referencing `users(id)`. `ON DELETE CASCADE` ensures sessions are automatically removed when a user is deleted.\n- `issued_at` defaults to now; `expires_at` is a required future timestamp.\n\n---\n\n#### 3. `003_add_session_index.sql` — Index on sessions.user_id\n**Applied:** 2025-01-22\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n\nAdds a B-tree index on `sessions.user_id` to speed up lookups of all sessions belonging to a given user — a common query pattern for session validation and logout-all-sessions operations.\n\n---\n\n### Migrations Recorded in History but Not Present (Archived)\n\nThe `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md` documents three additional migrations that ran in deployed environments but whose SQL files are no longer in the active `migrations/` directory (per the doc, they were moved to `migrations/archived/`, though that directory is also empty in this repo snapshot):\n\n| # | File | Date | Purpose |\n|---|------|------|---------|\n| 004 | `004_partition_users.sql` | 2025-02-18 | Range-partition `users` by `created_at` (monthly partitions) |\n| 005 | `005_archive_legacy_sessions.sql` | 2025-03-05 | Move sessions older than 90 days to a `sessions_archive` table |\n| 006 | `006_grant_readonly_role.sql` | 2025-04-12 | Create an `app_readonly` role and grant SELECT privileges |\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Order | Migration File | Purpose |\n|-------|---------------|---------|\n| 1 | `001_create_users.sql` | Create `users` table |\n| 2 | `002_create_sessions.sql` | Create `sessions` table with FK to users |\n| 3 | `003_add_session_index.sql` | Add index on `sessions.user_id` |\n\nThe three migrations build up a simple authentication data model: **users → sessions**, with a performance index added as a follow-up. The migration history document also attests to three later production migrations (partitioning, archival, and role grants) that are no longer source-controlled in the active migration directory.", "additional_kwargs": {